Bitcoin Financial Data Exploration¶

By Jeremiah Ikwuje¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

This document explores a dataset containing finanical information for the top 10 cryptocurrencies by marketcap from 2013-2019. Data was pulled from CoinMarketCap.com. Attributes of dataset include: Currency(e.g. bitcoin), Date, Open, Close, High, Low,, Volume, Market Cap.

Cleaning rows¶

Drop any row with multiple rows of same currency and date

In [14]:
currencies = df_copy['currency'].value_counts().index
for currency in currencies:
    coin = df_copy[(df_copy['currency'] == currency)]
    value_counts = coin['date'].value_counts().reset_index(name="count").query("count > 1")["index"]
    for date in value_counts:    
        # delete all rows with same column 'currency' and 'date' value
        indexAge = df_copy[ (df_copy['currency'] == currency) & (df_copy['date'] == date) ].index
        df_copy.drop(indexAge , inplace=True)

Drop any row in any numerical features with value 0 or less.

In [15]:
for feature in numeric_features:
    df_copy = df_copy[df_copy[feature] > 0]

All numerical column represent some form of value. I want all numerical features to have a positive monetary value for our analysis.

Feature Engineering (Creating new columns)¶

We are interested in knowing what time in year bitcoin performs better, when people invested in bitcoin the most, and which year bitcoin brought the highest return for investors?

However, our current dataset is limited to get this information. We will be adding three categorical features:

  1. year
  2. Quarters (Q1, Q2, Q3, Q4)
  3. months (January - December)

These categorical features will be derived from the date feature. All we are doing is simply to categorize the date feature by extracting the month, quarter, and year.

Price¶

We are also going to create a numerical column called price. This column is the average of the open, close, high, and low column. It will help viewers who are not deep in crypto to take the price column as the actual price of a crypto on each date. Also, it will create clarity in the analysis.

Create column in df_copy called year which extracts the year from the date column

In [17]:
df_copy['year'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(df_copy['date']).year

Create column in df_copy called month which extracts the year from the date column

In [18]:
df_copy['month'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(df_copy['date']).month_name()

Create column in df_copy called quarter which extracts the quarter from the date column

In [19]:
df_copy['quarter'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(df_copy['date']).quarter

Create column df_copy called price which is the average of the open, close, high, and low column.

In [20]:
df_copy['price'] = df_copy[['close', 'open', 'high', 'low']].mean(axis=1)

Market cap¶

Price is just one way to measure a cryptocurrency's value. Investors use market cap to tell a more complete story and compare value across cryptocurrencies. As a key statistic, it can indicate the growth potential of a cryptocurrency and whether it is safe to buy, compared to others.

In [32]:
sns.histplot(x='market_cap', data=df_btc).set(title="Market Cap in USD");

The distribution of the market cap data is rightly skewed. And there are several large values, so I like to define my own scale.

In [59]:
f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(7, 5))
sns.despine(f)

sns.histplot(
    data = df_btc,
    x="market_cap",
    linewidth=.5,
    log_scale=True,
    kde=True,
).set(title="Market Cap in USD")
ax.xaxis.set_major_formatter(mpl.ticker.ScalarFormatter())
ax.set_xticks([5e9, 1e10, 2e10, 5e10, 1e11, 2e11], [500, '1k', '2k', '5k', '10k', '20k']);

This gives us a clear picture of the distribution. The Bitcoin Market Cap distribution look bimodal. The data point peak between 500 to 1k and peak a little above 10K. Low points at the center between 2K to 5K and also a little above 20k.

Market cap between 500 - 1k is the major mode.

In [46]:
import math

def plot_line_btc_year(x, y, hue):
    """ Quick function to a grid of line plots """
    unique_years = [2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019]
    rows = math.ceil(len(unique_years) / 2)
    cols = 2
    count = 0
    
    # create figure
    fig = plt.figure(figsize= (15,9))

    for year in unique_years:
        count = count + 1
        df_btc_year = df_btc[df_btc['year'] == year].copy()
        df_btc_year['month_index'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(df_btc_year['date']).month
        
        # add subplot
        ax=fig.add_subplot(rows, cols, count)

        plt.subplot(rows, cols, count)
        # line plot bitcoin year performance data
        sns.lineplot(
            x=x, 
            y=y,
            data=df_btc_year,
            palette='bright',
            hue=hue,
            ax=ax).set(title=year);
    
    
    fig.tight_layout()  
    plt.show()

plot_line_btc_year(x='month_index', y='price', hue='quarter')
In [47]:
def bar_plot_btc_year(x, y, hue):
    """ Quick function to a grid of bar plots """
    unique_years = [2014, 2015, 2016, 2017, 2018, 2019]
    rows = math.ceil(len(unique_years) / 2)
    cols = 2
    count = 0
    
    # create figure
    fig = plt.figure(figsize= (15,9))
    palette = {1: "C0", 2: "C1", 3: "C2", 4: "k"}

    for year in unique_years:
        count = count + 1
        df_btc_year = df_btc[df_btc['year'] == year].copy()
        df_btc_year['month_index'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(df_btc_year['date']).month
        
        # add subplot
        ax=fig.add_subplot(rows, cols, count)

        plt.subplot(rows, cols, count)
        # bar plot bitcoin year performance data
        sns.barplot(
            x=x, 
            y=y, 
            data=df_btc_year,
            hue=hue,
            ax=ax,
            palette=palette).set(title=year)
    
    
    fig.tight_layout()  
    plt.show()

bar_plot_btc_year(x='month_index', y='price', hue='quarter');

The price of Bitcoin seems to perform better overall in Q3 (across the years)

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

A sharp increase in the price is usually followed up by a sharp decrease (and vice versa) as the date increase.
